The XPS analysis was performed to verify the elemental composition and chemical status of the DACT composite (Fig. 4
                        ). It could be observed in the survey spectrum from Fig. S2a that the DACT composite contained Ti, C, Ag, O and N at proportions of 48.87%, 4,45%, 4,16%, 42.03% and 0.48%, respectively. High-resolution spectrum of Ti 2p (Fig. 4a) could be separated as Ti 2p3/2 and Ti 2p1/2, which located in 458.0 eV and 463.7 eV, indicating the Ti4+ existing in TiO2 [27]. The composite showed typical peaks of CDs in C 1s spectrum (Fig. 4b). The peaks located at 284.5 eV, 286.3 eV and 288.1 eV could be indexed to the graphitic C (C–C), hydroxylated surface carbon atoms (C–OH) and the sp2 hybridized C (N–C–N) [62,63]. The formation of N–C–N bond further confirming the doping of N in CDs. Seen from the Ag 3d spectrum in Fig. 4c, there are two peaks at about 367 eV and 373 eV, which could be indexed to Ag 3d5/2 and Ag 3d3/2 orbitals. The peaks at 367.2 eV and 373.2 eV could be attributed to Ag+ in Ag2O, and the other two weak peaks were assigned to metallic Ag, originating from the synthesis process by the reduction of Ag+ with the help of NaBH4. The XPS results of Ag 3d demonstrated that the atom ratio of Ag in DACT was 4 at%, and the ratio of Ag and Ag+ was about 1:3 (Table 1
                        ), which means the Ag+ was the dominant part in Ag/Ag2O system. Hence, with the synergetic effect of Ag/Ag+, the photostability and the migration of photoinduced carriers will be improved and thus enhancing the photocatalytic performance [25]. The O 1s spectrum was fitted by two peaks (Fig. 4d). The major one at 529.1 eV could be ascribed to the oxygen lattices in TiO2, while the weak one could attribute to Ag2O [64,65]. The N 1s peak in Fig. S2b with the binding energy at around 399.2 eV could assigned to sp2-hybridized C–N–C [66], which was in consistent with the C 1s result.
